FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - MOZAMBIQUE: OIE ALERT
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Thu, 07 Nov 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Animal Health Information Department, Office international
des epizooties (OIE) [edited]
<information.dept@oie.int>

Suspected Foot & Mouth disease in Mozambique
---------------------------------------------
(Date of previous reported outbreak: 1985).
Text of an e-mail received on 7 Nov 2002 from Dr Francisco Gomes
Pinto, Head of the Animal Health Department, Ministry of Agriculture,
Maputo:
Report date: 6 Nov 2002.
Affected animals: bovine.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 4 Nov 2002.
Estimated date of first infection: 20 Aug 2002
Suspected clinical Foot and Mouth Disease has been detected in three
kraals situated in an area with communal grazing land in the district
of Manhica, Maputo Province. Investigations are in progress to
determine the extent of the affected population.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
- Susceptible: 400.
- Cases: 20
Causal agent: unknown, SAT virus suspected.
Source of agent / Origin of infection: under investigation.
Control measures:
- Manhica district in the Maputo province has been placed under quarantine;
- Movement control in the adjacent areas;
- Vaccination of all cattle in the Manhica district (8500 vaccinated
heads) is being carried out and surveillance has been intensified in
this district.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[During 2002, FMD has been reported to the OIE by 3 of Mozambique's
neighbouring countries, namely Zambia, Zimbabwe, and Swaziland. The
most recent information (11 Oct 2002) was reported by Zimbabwe,
mentioning SAT 2 virus infection as suspected. The deterioration of
the FMD situation in Southern Africa was discussed in a previous
ProMED-mail posting. - Mod.AS]
